**********************************
Introducing... the Law of Locality
**********************************

The Law of Locality says put UI controls where they effect
change.

So if you have actions that effect change on an email (e.g. Star,
Archive, Delete), display those actions on the email.

=E2=80=8B
Likewise, if you have actions that effect change on a folder
(like Rename or Delete), where should you put those?

On the folder.

OK, technically it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Con a MENU that appears from folder=E2=
=80=9D, close
enough
But in addition to emails and folder, the Law of Locality also
applies to more conceptual =E2=80=9Cobjects=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 like, for in=
stance,
accounts.

Where do you put account actions (like =E2=80=9CSign out=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=
=9CModify
account=E2=80=9D, etc)?

Say it with me: on the account.

=E2=80=8B
Notice how the account is at the very top of the page? That leads
to the second part of the law of locality:

If an element acts on a GROUP or AREA, put it ABOVE that
group/area.

Again, this is easy to see in Gmail with multi-email actions
(=E2=80=9CMark all as read=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9CRefresh inbox=E2=80=9D, etc.)

=E2=80=8B
One of the most important facets of the second law of locality is
that it=E2=80=99s recursive: areas can be nested in each other.

For instance, where=E2=80=99s the search bar?

It=E2=80=99s above the actions we just talked about=E2=80=A6

=E2=80=8B
=E2=80=A6because it applies over a broader conceptual surface than the
buttons.

("Search" applies over all emails; "Mark as read" only applies to
emails in the current view)

And kid, let me tell ya =F0=9F=A4=A0=E2=80=A6 it=E2=80=99s the Law of Local=
ity all the way
up.

